resource "aws_glue_catalog_table" "example_table" {
  name      = "ExampleTableName"
  database  = "your-glue-database"

  // Open Contributor Insights and specify a few settings
  storage_descriptor {
    location = "s3://your-bucket-name/path-to-your-data"
    struct_type {
      field_name = "your-field-name"
      field_type = "string"
      # Add more fields as needed
    }
  }

  input {
    format    = "parquet"
  }

  parameters {
    allowPublicBrowsing = false
    partitions       = true
    partitionKeys = ["yourPartitionKey"]
  }

  physical_partition_prefix = {
    prefix = "your-partition-prefix" // Specify your partitioning if applicable
  }

  connection = {
    type           = "custom"
    connect_type   = "jdbc" // Specify the type of connection
    password      = "your-jdbc-password"
    user = "your-jdbc-username"
    additional_settings = [
      {
        name = "JDBC_CONNECTION_URL"
        value = "jdbc:your-jdbc-connectivity-string"
      }
    ]
  }

  tbl_input {
    connection          = aws_glue_catalog_table.connection
    columns            = ["your-column-names..."] // specify your column names
    date_partitioned  = true
    partition_keys     = ["yourPartitionKey"]
  }
}

response:
To turn on the Amazon Contributor Insights feature for a table in the AWS Glue Data Catalog, you need to use the `aws_glue_table` resource in Terraform. Here's how you can define the Terraform configuration for achieving this:

```hcl
resource "aws_glue_catalog_table" "example_table" {
  name      = "ExampleTableName"
  database  = "your-glue-database"

  // Open Contributor Insights and specify a few settings
  storage_descriptor {
    location = "s3://your-bucket-name/path-to-your-data"
    struct_type {
      field_name = "your-field-name"
      field_type = "string"
      # Add more fields as needed
    }
  }

  input {
    format    = "parquet"
  }

  parameters {
    allowPublicBrowsing = false
    partitions       = true
    partitionKeys = ["yourPartitionKey"]
  }

  physical_partition_prefix = {
    prefix = "your-partition-prefix" // Specify your partitioning if applicable
  }

  connection = {
    type           = "custom"
    connect_type   = "jdbc" // Specify the type of connection
    password      = "your-jdbc-password"
    user = "your-jdbc-username"
    additional_settings = [
      {
        name = "JDBC_CONNECTION_URL"
        value = "jdbc:your-jdbc-connectivity-string"
      }
    ]
  }

  tbl_input {
    connection          = aws_glue_catalog_table.connection
    columns            = ["your-column-names..."] // specify your column names
    date_partitioned  = true
    partition_keys     = ["yourPartitionKey"]
  }
}
```

In this configuration:

- Replace `"your-glue-database"`, `"s3://your-bucket-name/path-to-your-data"`, `"your-field-name"`, `"yourPartitionKey"`, `"your-column-names..."`, `"your-partition-prefix"`, `"your-jdbc-connectivity-string"`, `"your-jdbc-username"`, and `"your-jdbc-password"` with actual values pertinent to your AWS Glue Catalog table setup.
- These settings turn on the use of partitions and specify which fields form part of the data structure, and the required connection configurations to activate Contributor Insights for external datasets. The `allow_public_browsing` should be set to `false` to prevent public access.

