response:
To create an Amazon S3 Glacier vault intended for long-term data storage using Terraform, you can define the resource in your configuration as follows:

```hcl
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "long_term_storage" {
  bucket = "my-long-term-glacier-vault"
  acl    = "private"

  logging {
    target_prefix = "http://example.com/bucket-logs/"
  }

  versioning {
    enabled = true
  }

  lifecycle {
    prevent_destroy = true
  }

  force_destroy = false
  rule {
    id        = "1"
    status    = "Enabled"
    filter_scope = "Bucket"
    filter {
      prefix = ""
    }
    expiration = {
      days   = 365
    }
    transitions = [
      {
        days          = 30
        storage_class = "GLACIER"
      },
    ]
  }
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "long_term_glacier" {
  bucket        = aws_s3_bucket.long_term_storage.bucket
  versioning {
    enabled = true
  }
  lifecycle {
    prevent_destroy = true
  }
  force_destroy = false
}
```

In this configuration:

- The S3 bucket is created with versioning enabled, which is crucial for long-term storage.
- Lifecycle rules are configured to transition objects automatically to the S3 Glacier storage class after 30 days, and ensure the objects are expired after 365 days to enforce deletion.
- Logging is configured to track requests made to the bucket.
- `prevent_destroy` is set to `true` to prevent accidental deletion of the bucket.
- `force_destroy` is set to `false` to adhere to the 3-year retention requirement specified by S3 Glacier, allowing objects to be deleted only when they have been explicitly expired and archived retention period lapse.

This configuration leverages AWS S3's capabilities with improvements for archival and lifecycle management, fitting the speculative requirements for long-term data storage using S3 Glacier.

