response:
To create an AWS-based storage solution for long-term data retention and backups, you can use AWS S3 for storage and AWS Backup for backup and long-term retention. Here is the Terraform configuration for setting up an S3 bucket and a backup vault using randomly generated IDs:

```hcl
resource "random_string" "backup_performance" {
  length  = 32
  special = false
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "data_retention" {
  bucket = "my-long-term-data-bucket-${random_string.backup_performance.result}"
  acl    = "private"
}

resource "aws_backup_vault" "long_term_retention" {
  name = "my-backup-vault-${random_string.backup_performance.result}"
  type = "cross-region"
}

resource "aws_backup_plan" "default_retention_plan" {
  name = "my-backup-plan"

  rule {
    rule_name              = "my-backup-rule"
    target_vault          = aws_backup_vault.long_term_retention.id
    lifecycle {
      delete_after        = 30 // Days
      cold_storage_after = 30 // Days
    }
  }
}
```

This configuration creates an S3 bucket for long-term data retention with a unique name generated using `random_string`, and configures a Backup Vault to enable long-term retention policies through AWS Backup. All these components are part of AWS infrastructure keeping your data safe and making it manageable for backup and retention.

Note: The ACLs and policies are simplified and should be adjusted based on your exact needs in production, especially regarding permissions and lifecycle configurations.

